    <article class="article">
      <h1>Bee anatomy</h1>
      <p class="lede">External and internal structures that drive behaviour and colony work.</p>

      <div class="grid cols-3">
        <section class="card" id="external">
          <h2>External features</h2>
          <ul class="list">
            <li><strong>Head:</strong> compound eyes for light and motion, <a href="/wiki/foundations/glossary-antenna.html">antennae</a> for smell and touch, proboscis for nectar.</li>
            <li><strong>Thorax:</strong> anchor point for wings and legs; flight muscles live here.</li>
            <li><strong>Abdomen:</strong> contains wax glands (workers), sting apparatus (workers/queen), and digestive organs.</li>
            <li><strong>Wing coupling:</strong> tiny hooks (hamuli) link fore and hind wings for efficient flight.</li>
            <li><strong>Pollen baskets:</strong> workersâ€™ hind legs form <em>corbiculae</em> to carry pollen.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="card" id="internal">
          <h2>Internal systems</h2>
          <ul class="list">
            <li><strong>Digestive:</strong> honey stomach (crop) for nectar transport, midgut for digestion.</li>
            <li><strong>Circulatory:</strong> open system; haemolymph pumped by a dorsal vessel.</li>
            <li><strong>Respiratory:</strong> spiracles and tracheae deliver oxygen without lungs.</li>
            <li><strong>Nervous:</strong> brain and segmental ganglia coordinate complex behaviour.</li>
            <li><strong>Glands:</strong> mandibular, Nasonov, wax glands influence communication and work.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="card" id="differences">
          <h2>Worker, queen, drone â€” key differences</h2>
          <ul class="list">
            <li><strong>Worker:</strong> pollen baskets, wax glands, barbed sting; varied age-based roles.</li>
            <li><strong>Queen:</strong> longer abdomen for egg laying; smooth sting; pheromone production.</li>
            <li><strong>Drone:</strong> large eyes, no sting or pollen baskets; body built for mating flight.</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="muted">See also: <a href="/wiki/foundations/bee-castes-and-lifecycle.html">Bee castes &amp; lifecycle</a>.</p>
        </section>
      </div>

      <div class="divider"></div>

      <section id="senses">
        <h2>Senses & communication</h2>
        <ul class="list">
          <li><strong>Smell:</strong> antennae detect pheromones for orientation, alarm, and queen presence.</li>
          <li><strong>Vision:</strong> ultraviolet patterns on flowers guide foraging.</li>
          <li><strong>Vibration:</strong> substrate-borne signals help coordinate work inside the hive.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="notice">Tip: scented markers (Nasonov pheromone) help returning foragers find the entrance in poor weather.</p>
      </section>

      <section id="practical">
        <h2>Practical beekeeping implications</h2>
        <ul class="list">
          <li><strong>Handling:</strong> avoid blocking spiracles; gentle smoke masks alarm pheromone.</li>
          <li><strong>Inspection:</strong> brood pattern and abdomen shape help assess queen status.</li>
          <li><strong>Foraging:</strong> full pollen baskets indicate strong forage; wax scale suggests comb building.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

